                    <h3 class="ui center aligned header">AI Notebook also has standard features including achievements, 
                        daily writing streaks, and tagging. We use end-to-end encryption and partner with
                        trusted organizations for maximum security. 
                    </h3>
                </div>
            </div>
    
            <div class="ui container mission">
                <h1 class="ui center aligned inverted header" id="mission">Writing down your thoughts in an unstructured way every day is a powerful way to find peace, happiness, and mental clarity.</h1>
            </div>
            
            <div class="ui hidden divider"></div>
            
            <h4 class="ui horizontal green inverted header divider">
                The Evidence
            </h4>
            <div class="ui lander-padded container">
                <div class="ui three column stackable grid">
                    <div class="column">
                        <div class="ui inverted segment">
                            <h2 class="ui center aligned header">Expressing our emotions helps us to control them.</h2>
                            <p class="landing-p">A 2007 UCLA study focused on the reaction of the amygdala, the brain’s alarm system, when participants were shown pictures of angry or fearful faces. Some were asked to describe each face’s emotion as it appeared, and others simply observed. Their brain activity was studied using fMRI. <strong>Participants who described what they were observing showed a decreased fear response.</strong></p>
                            <p class="landing-p">Labelling emotions also activated a part of the brain associated with emotion processing and self-inhibition.</p>
                            <a href="https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/06/070622090727.htm" target="_blank">University of California - Los Angeles. "Putting Feelings Into Words Produces Therapeutic Effects In The Brain." ScienceDaily. ScienceDaily, 22 June 2007. <www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/06/070622090727.htm>.</a>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="column">
                        <div class="ui inverted segment">
                            <h2 class="ui center aligned header">Writing can help us recover from difficult events.</h2>
                            <p class="landing-p">
                                In 1991, an experiment was conducted involving 41 people who were recently laid off. They were divided into three groups- one was not given special instructions; one was instructed to write about their day; and a third was asked to write about their deepest thoughts and emotions surrounding the job loss and their job search. The third group showed mich higher job placement rates compared to the other two after eight months.
                            </p>
                            <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/256708" target="_blank">Spera, Stefanie P., et al. “Expressive Writing and Coping with Job Loss.” The Academy of Management Journal, vol. 37, no. 3, 1994, pp. 722–733. JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/256708.</a>
                          </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="column">
                        <div class="ui inverted segment">
                            <h2 class="ui center aligned header">Writing can improve overall health.</h2>
                            <p class="landing-p">
                                Another experiment had participants engage in 15-minute writing sessions for three days. Those who wrote about emotional or traumatic experiences reported that although the writing may have been distressing, they considered the experience very valuable and would do it again. These participants also exhibited increases in mental and physical health.
                            </p>
                            <a href="http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=mdc&AN=11045774&site=ehost-live" target="_blank">Pennebaker, J. W., and J. D. Seagal. “Forming a Story: The Health Benefits of Narrative.” Journal Of Clinical Psychology, vol. 55, no. 10, Oct. 1999, pp. 1243–1254. EBSCOhost, search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=mdc&AN=11045774&site=ehost-live.</a>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="ui inverted center aligned segment">
                    <h3 class="ui inverted header">
                        Numerous other studies have affirmed the ability of personal and emotional writing to improve long-term mood and even physical health. 
                    </h3>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ui hidden divider"></div>
        </div>
